State as a Snapshot explains why this is happening. Setting state requests a new re-render, but does not change it in the already running code. So score continues to be 0 right after you call setScore(score + 1).

console.log(score);  // 0

setScore(score + 1); // setScore(0 + 1);

console.log(score);  // 0

setScore(score + 1); // setScore(0 + 1);

console.log(score);  // 0

setScore(score + 1); // setScore(0 + 1);

console.log(score);  // 0

You can fix this by passing an updater function when setting state. Notice how replacing setScore(score + 1) with setScore(s => s + 1) fixes the ‚Äú+3‚Äù button. This lets you queue multiple state updates.

